<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-107-200  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 107 200.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Nov 6 1989 v3 n45 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Developing computer usage accounting procedures.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Linder, Bill R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Accurate usage accounting and billing information increasesefficiency and effectiveness in MIS facilities by encouragingmanaged use of computer systems.andP;  Purchasing measurement softwareto monitor use of each service is recommended, and both automatedand manual techniques are typically required for metering.andO;Monitoring service usage can be problematic because each piece ofhardware can have its own measurement software, and becausemetering capabilities can limit the design of the charging system.andO;A central approach to usage reporting is usually most effectivebecause it reduces costs for software support, reduces theprocessing load, and ensures standard billing output.andP;  Completeusage and cost reports should show use of services along withassociated charges for each group of users.andP;  Year-to-date figuresand summarized information should also be provided.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Usage MeasurementManagement of EDPGuidelinesComputing AccountingReportsEnd UsersEfficiency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>